#
# Aegis eol policy. Forces LF in the repo for
# every text file. Windows-native scripts keep
# CRLF because PowerShell + cmd.exe require it.
#
# Why this file exists
# --------------------
# Windows + core.autocrlf=true was producing
# CRLF in the working tree for almost every file
# (253 of 308 at the time of writing), even
# though the canonical repo is LF. The local
# `gofmt -l` run on Windows then flagged
# every Go file as "incorrect" (the diff was
# purely CRLF -> LF), so every `golangci-lint`
# run looked broken even though CI on Linux was
# green. Pinning the eol in the repo fixes that:
# Git will hand every contributor LF, regardless
# of their `core.autocrlf` setting.
#
# EOL matrix
# ----------
# *                         LF (default for text)
# *.bat, *.cmd              CRLF (Windows batch)
# *.ps1                    CRLF (PowerShell on Windows)
# *.sh                     LF (already default, but explicit)
# Binary files             left to Git's autodetect
#
# After this file lands, every contributor should
# run `git add --renormalize . && git commit`
# once so the working tree matches the repo's
# canonical eol. The follow-up commit is empty
# for users already on a clean LF tree and large
# (~250 files, ~3k lines) for everyone else.

*                 text=auto eol=lf
*.bat             text eol=crlf
*.cmd             text eol=crlf
*.ps1             text eol=crlf
*.sh              text eol=lf

# Binary formats (no eol)
*.png             binary
*.jpg             binary
*.jpeg            binary
*.gif             binary
*.ico             binary
*.webp            binary
*.woff            binary
*.woff2           binary
*.ttf             binary
*.eot             binary
